\title{Jepsen Testing}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{Jepsen-style correctness testing for distributed systems under faults (partitions, crashes, clock skew) using concurrent operation histories and formal checkers (linearizability/serializability and Elle-style anomalies). Use when designing, implementing, or running Jepsen tests, or interpreting histories/violations.}

\subtree{
\title{Jepsen Testing}
\subtree{
\title{Intake}
\ul{
\li{Identify the system under test and the exact client surface (Redis, S3, Kafka, HTTP, gRPC).}
\li{Define what "acknowledged" means for each operation (what does the client treat as committed).}
\li{Write the claimed consistency guarantees as a checkable property (linearizable register, RYW, monotonic reads, serializable txns).}
\li{Specify the failure model to test (crash-stop, partitions, clock skew, disk stalls, restarts).}
\li{Decide whether the test must be multi-surface (write via Redis, read via S3) to validate cross-frontend coherence.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Workload Design}
\ul{
\li{Prefer the smallest workload that can falsify the claim.}
\li{Use a mix of reads and writes that creates ambiguous interleavings.}
\li{Add a "witness" invariant that is easy to explain:}
\li{Lost acknowledged write.}
\li{Read sees a value that cannot be explained by any sequential execution respecting real-time order.}
\li{List-append: element lost/duplicated or observed order implies a cycle.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Checker Selection}
\ul{
\li{Register or map semantics: use a linearizability checker.}
\li{Transactional / multi-object semantics: use Elle-style anomaly detection (write cycles, dirty reads, lost updates).}
\li{If linearizability is too strong for the product, explicitly select a weaker model and encode it (do not silently downgrade).}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Fault (Nemesis) Selection}
\ul{
\li{Partitions: majority/minority splits, bridge partitions, flapping partitions.}
\li{Process faults: kill and restart, node reboot, rolling restarts.}
\li{Time faults: clock offsets and jumps if the system relies on time.}
\li{Storage faults: fsync latency, I/O stalls, disk-full behavior (only if safe and reversible).}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Run and Minimize}
\ul{
\li{Start with a short, low-concurrency run until the harness is stable.}
\li{When a failure appears, minimize by reducing:}
\li{Keys, operation count, and concurrency.}
\li{Fault intensity and schedule complexity.}
\li{Preserve determinism (fixed seeds, fixed partition schedule) so a failing history can be reproduced.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Reporting}
\ul{
\li{State the exact claim under test and the precise pass/fail property.}
\li{Include the workload, nemesis schedule, and a minimal failing history excerpt.}
\li{Distinguish availability failures (timeouts) from safety failures (incorrect ok results).}
}
}
}